"Colwell R.K., Brehm G., Cardelús C.L., Gilman A.C., Longino J.T.","Global warming, elevational range shifts, and lowland biotic attrition in the wet tropics",2008,"Science","322","5899",,"258","261",,,10.1126/science.1162547,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53749094032&partnerID=40&md5=c64b460548873fb0ea21f33adb0bdb82","Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of Connecticut, Storrs, CT 06269, United States; Institut für Spezielle Zoologie und Evolutionsbiologie Mit Phyletischem Museum, Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena, Erbertstraße 1, 07743 Jena, Germany; Department of Biology, Colgate University, Hamilton, NY 13346, United States; Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90950, United States; Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA 98505, United States","Colwell, R.K., Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of Connecticut, Storrs, CT 06269, United States; Brehm, G., Institut für Spezielle Zoologie und Evolutionsbiologie Mit Phyletischem Museum, Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena, Erbertstraße 1, 07743 Jena, Germany; Cardelús, C.L., Department of Biology, Colgate University, Hamilton, NY 13346, United States; Gilman, A.C., Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, University of California, Los Angeles, CA 90950, United States; Longino, J.T., Evergreen State College, Olympia, WA 98505, United States","Many studies suggest that global warming is driving species ranges poleward and toward higher elevations at temperate latitudes, but evidence for range shifts is scarce for the tropics, where the shallow latitudinal temperature gradient makes upslope shifts more likely than poleward shifts. Based on new data for plants and insects on an elevational transect in Costa Rica, we assess the potential for lowland biotic attrition, range-shift gaps, and mountaintop extinctions under projected warming. We conclude that tropical lowland biotas may face a level of net lowland biotic attrition without parallel at higher latitudes (where range shifts may be compensated for by species from lower latitudes) and that a high proportion of tropical species soon faces gaps between current and projected elevational ranges.",,"elevation; extinction; global warming; insect; plant; population distribution; temperature gradient; tropical environment; article; biotic stress; climate change; Costa Rica; evolutionary adaptation; gel electrophoresis; geographic elevation; greenhouse effect; high temperature; nonhuman; prediction; priority journal; species difference; species extinction; species richness; tropics; warming; Acclimatization; Altitude; Animal Migration; Animals; Ants; Biodiversity; Costa Rica; Demography; Ecosystem; Geography; Greenhouse Effect; Insects; Moths; Plants; Population Dynamics; Rubiaceae; Temperature; Tropical Climate; Central America; Costa Rica; Hexapoda",,,,,,"Parmesan, C., (2006) Annu. Rev. Ecol. Evol. Syst, 37, p. 637; Wilson, R., Gutierrez, D., Gutierrez, J., Monserrat, V., (2007) Glob. Change Biol, 13, p. 1873; Lenoir, J., Gegout, J., Marquet, P., de Ruffray, P., Brisse, H., (2008) Science, 320, p. 1768; Bush, M.B., (2002) Glob. Ecol. Biogeogr, 11, p. 463; Materials and methods are available as supporting material on Science OnlineBush, M.B., Hooghiemstra, H., (2005) Climate Change and Biodiversity, pp. 125-137. , T. E. Lovejoy, L. Hannah, Eds, Yale Univ. Press, New Haven, CT; Pounds, J.A., Fogden, M.P.L., Masters, K.L., (2005) Climate Change and Biodiversity, pp. 70-74. , T. E. Lovejoy, L. Hanna, Eds, Yale Univ. Press, New Haven, CT; Cardelús, C.L., Colwell, R.K., Watkins, J.E., (2006) J. Ecol, 94, p. 144; Brehm, G., Colwell, R.K., Kluge, J., (2007) Glob. Ecol. Biogeogr, 16, p. 205; Wallace, A.R., (1878) Tropical Nature and Other Essays, , Macmillan, London; Dobzhansky, T., (1950) Am. Sci, 38, p. 209; Hannah, L., Betts, R.A., Shugart, H.H., (2007) Tropical Rainforest Responses to Climatic Change, pp. 351-366. , 